        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We propose to observe the thermal continuum emission of the disk of the
Butterfly star at 135 GHz (2222 µm) using ALMA band 4 in the currently offered
C34-7 array configuration. We consider the maximum bandwidth of 7.5 GHz. All
four spectral windows shall operate in the TDM mode with dual polarization to
maximize the sensitivity. The spectral resolution is considered to be 31.25 MHz.
Mosaic imaging is not required because the total extend of the Butterfly star
disk on the sky (~4.5") is within the inner third of the primary beam (14.52").
The largest structure that is intended to be resolved is one half of the disk,
corresponding to an angular scale of ~2.3", which is smaller than the maximum
recoverable scale of this ALMA configuration in band 4 of 6.4". All estimations
on angular scales have been checked with CASA 4.2. observing simulations
(details below).

From an interpolation between the measured continuum fluxes, which are the
closest to the proposed wavelength (PdBI: (101 +- 10) mJy at 1.3 mm, OVRO: (22
+- 2) mJy at 2.7 mm; see Graefe et al., 2013), and the prediction of the best
fit model by Graefe et al. (2013) the continuum flux at 2 mm is estimated to be
at least 33.5 mJy. The faintest peak continuum flux per beam is 0.55 mJy/beam
(best fit model by Graefe et al., 2013). Achieving a signal to noise ratio of at
least 10, the required sensitivity is 0.05 mJy corresponding to an on-source
time of 6 min. Including all overheads and calibrator source observations the
required total time for this science goal is ~0.5 h.

Additionally, we simulated a synthetic ALMA map at 135 GHz (2222 µm) and an
on-source time of 6 min for the array configuration C34-7. This simulation
includes the influence of thermal and phase noise through the water vapour in
the atmosphere by PWV = (2.748 +- 0.2) mm. It ensures the feasibility to resolve
all important structures in the disk and an acceptable u-v coverage of the
proposed observation.

The data rate of 2.2 MB/s is acceptable.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
