        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We propose to observe the thermal continuum emission of the disk of the
Butterfly star at 233 GHz (1287 µm) using ALMA band 6 in the currently offered
C34-7 array configuration. We consider the maximum bandwidth of 7.5 GHz. All
four spectral windows shall operate in the TDM mode with dual polarization to
maximize the sensitivity. The spectral resolution is considered to be 31.25 MHz.
Mosaic imaging is not required because the total extend of the Butterfly star
disk on the sky (~4.5") is within the inner third of the primary beam (8.52").
The largest structure that is intended to be resolved is one half of the disk,
corresponding to an angular scale of ~2.3", which is smaller than the maximum
recoverable scale of this ALMA configuration in band 6 of 3.8". All estimations
on angular scales have been checked with CASA 4.2. observing simulations
(details below).

The integrated continuum flux of the Butterfly Star at 1.3 mm
is (101 +- 10) mJy as obtained by Graefe et al. (2013) using the PdBI with a
beam size of 0.59"x0.35". Considering a beam size of the proposed ALMA band 6
observation of 0.17"x0.17", a faintest peak continuum flux per beam of interest
of 1 mJy/beam, and a signal to noise ration of at least 30, the require
sensitivity is 0.03 mJy, corresponding to an on-source time of 25 min. Including
all overheads and calibrator source observations the required total time for
this science goal is ~1 h.

Additionally, we simulated a synthetic ALMA map at 233 GHz (1287 µm) and an
on-source time of 25 min for the array configuration C34-7. This simulation
includes the influence of thermal and phase noise through the water vapour in
the atmosphere by PWV = (1.262 +- 0.15) mm. It ensures the feasibility to
resolve all important structures in the disk and a sufficient u-v coverage of
the proposed observation.

The data rate of 2.2 MB/s is acceptable.</prj:justificationText>
