        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We propose to observe the thermal continuum emission of the disk of the
Butterfly star at 343.5 GHz (872.7 µm) using ALMA band 7 in the currently
offered C34-7 array configuration. We consider the maximum bandwidth of 7.5 GHz.
All four spectral windows shall operate in the TDM mode with dual polarization
to maximize the sensitivity. The spectral resolution is considered to be 31.25
MHz. Mosaic imaging is not required because the total extend of the Butterfly
star disk on the sky (~4.5") is within the inner third of the primary beam
(5.91"). The largest structure that is intended to be resolved is one half of
the disk, corresponding to an angular scale of ~2.3", which is smaller than the
maximum recoverable scale of this ALMA configuration in band 7 of 2.6". All
estimations on angular scales have been checked with CASA 4.2. observing
simulations (details below).

Close to the proposed frequency of 343.5 GHz (872.8 µm) the continuum flux of
the object was measured at 335 GHz (894 µm) with the SMA (Wolf et al., 2008). It
amounts to 287 mJy with an rms noise of 3.3 mJy/beam and a beam size of
0.67"x0.53". To additionally estimate the significance of a minimum in the
disk's brightness profile of this observation (see Fig. 2 in the Science case
document), a twice times better sensitivity is required. With the considered
beam size of the ALMA band 7 observation of 0.12"x0.12" this amounts to a
sensitivity of 0.047 mJy. Based on this sensitivity we estimated the
corresponding on-source time of 25 min with the ALMA sensitivity calculator.
Including all overheads and calibrator source observations the required total
time for this science goal is 1.12 h.

Additionally, we simulated a synthetic ALMA map at 343.5 GHz (872.7 µm) and an
on-source time of 25 min for the array configuration C34-7 (see Fig. 3 in the
Science case document). This simulation includes the influence of thermal and
phase noise through the water vapour in the atmosphere by PWV = (0.66 +- 0.1)
mm. It ensures the feasibility to resolve all important structures in the disk
and a sufficient u-v coverage of the proposed observation.

The data rate of 2.2 MB/s is acceptable.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
