    <prp:abstract>
Dust grain growth and evolution as well as the distribution of dust grains affect the (sub)mm emission appearance of protoplanetary disks (Boehler et al.,2013). In particular, dust settling in the vertical direction of the disk can be best investigated in the case of disks in edge-on orientation.

We propose to observe and to spatially resolve the prominent edge-on protoplanetary disk of the Butterfly star with the goal to determine the vertical and radial distribution of large dust grains down to a scale of ~16 AU. Our goal will be achieved by continuum emission observations in ALMA bands 4,6, &amp; 7 with the most extended array configuration available in ALMA cycle 2. 

The main outcome of these observations will be a significantly improved understanding of the vertical and radial structure of the dust phase and its evolution in protoplanetary disks, potentially serving as a reference for corresponding theoretical models.

The feasibility of these observations is ensured by previous observations (e.g., Wolf et al.,2003,2008; Gräfe et al.,2013) and dedicated preparatory modeling (Boehler et al.,2013; Gräfe et al.,2013).</prp:abstract>
